  <h1>Jamestown: Culture</h1>
  <p><em>It is important to note that despite the Jamestown colony's location it retained many of the social structures and institutions originating from the old world.</em></p>
</header>

<section>
  <h2>Social Hierarchy</h2>
  <p>
    Jamestown was a unique place and agathokakological, in the sense that it was the purest form of syncretism. It had evils. It had great goods, that would be adopted by the future union. 
    Jamestown's society was marked by a clear social hierarchy influenced by English class structures. The colony included aristocrats, tradesmen, indentured servants, and enslaved Africans. This social stratification shaped interactions and power dynamics within the settlement. <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/colonial-america/jamestown" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">History.com: Jamestown</a> offers an excellent overview of these dynamics.
  </p>
  <p>
    The earliest settlers had little to no experience with hard labour. This created tense and strained relationship beetween the working classes. But as time came to pass, skilled labourours mended this relationship. 
  </p>
