<section>
  <h2>Relations with Native Americans</h2>
  <p>
    The Powhatan confederacy was inextricably entwined with the cultural ethos of the Jamestown settlers. These interactions consisted of the following: alliances (often uneasy), commerc and war. The Powhatan people were located aroudn the Virginia since times of great antiquity, in which our historical records are unable to penetrate due to lack of writing systems. The Powhatan people were a remarkable people both in their deep knowledge of local flaura, fauna, and agricultural techniques but also their benevolence in assisting the settler's through famine.</p>
  <p>
    However, cultural misunderstandings and territorial disputes led to periodic clashes, culminating in the Anglo-Powhatan Wars. For more on these relations, see the Smithsonian's <a href="https://americanhistory.si.edu/collections/object-groups/jamestown-1607" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Jamestown Collection</a>.
  </p>
