<section>
  <h2>Religion and Daily Life</h2>
  <p>
    Religion was integral to Jamestown culture. And you may note that settlers were English Anglicans, and daily life included worship and adherence to moral codes. What is morality? 
    That is a difficult question but due to their theistic belief the settlers were able to make claims about objective morality and able to mantain rough social cohesion due to their unification in one faith.

  </p>
  <p>
    Charles Dickens begins his tale of tow cities by saying, "It was the best of times; It was the worst of times". Dickens exemplifies how tumultuos times often are a juxtaposition of differing situations. Jamestown is an extroardinary example of this. The famous "Starving Time" (1609-1610) nearly destroyed the colony, but suprisingly morale and societal cohesion improved. For a more nuanced perspective you may refrence the following: <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Jamestown" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Encyclopedia Britannica: Jamestown</a>.
  </p>
